Chain reaction 🔗⚓ Dive beneath crystal blue waters and discover the Chaine d’ancre motif. A house signature since 1938, seen today in Le Monde d'Hermès.​

The story behind: In 1937, Robert Dumas watched boats as he strolled along the Normandy coast. The anchor chains that held them in place caught his eye and inspired the shape of the iconic Chaine d'ancre motif. This exemplifies the "intelligence of the eye" and the harmonious balance between practicality and beauty that is quintessential to the Hermès philosophy. It was in 1938 when the Maison ventured into uncharted waters and crafted the first silver Chaine d'ancre bracelet. Since then, this motif has been an endless source of inspiration, undergoing a plethora of interpretations, utilizing various materials and shapes, all while preserving its essence.​

3D illustration by berenicegolmann​

The #DiorWinter23 campaign masterfully interprets one of the collection’s main storylines, where an old world meets a new one, in change and in flux. Blending poetic simplicity and extreme precision, a quest for elegance, comfort and functionality pervades the collection. Declined in a sea of grays, silhouettes are softened, curved and malleable while clothes are hybridized and metamorphosed, from the 'Passe Partout' coat in Donegal tweed with zipped open sleeves to nods to British tailoring traditions and materials that evoke a haute couture tailleur.
© RafaelPavarotti_

Shot against a stormy gray decor in the new #DiorWinter23 campaign, a maritime-inspired look by MrKimJones pays tribute to Yves Saint Laurent's groundbreaking debut collection for Dior for Spring-Summer 1958, characterized by a streamlining of excess. Final touches include a revisited fisherman's rain hat by StephenJonesMillinery and the sleek new Dior Pillow bag which tucks under the arm, capturing the very essence of fashion: the beautifully useful. 
© RafaelPavarotti_

For the #DiorWinter23 campaign, photographer RafaelPavarotti_ captures a mood of transformation and flux, with MrKimJones exploring the House's rejuvenation under Yves Saint Laurent through the symbol of the Thames and Seine rivers, flowing from country to city to sea. Maritime references abound, from Aran cable knits with split sleeves to revisited fisherman smocks, while volume plays and drapes on sleeves evoke undulating waves.

In the #DiorWinter23 campaign by RafaelPavarotti_, archetypal utilitarian outerwear looks by MrKimJones celebrate contemporary elegance through the lens of Dior savoir-faire, offering a startlingly modern counterpoint to the line’s archival references.

Photographer RafaelPavarotti_ captures the essence of the #DiorWinter23 collection by MrKimJones in his latest campaign for the House. Silhouettes are softened, curved and malleable and clothes are hybridized and metamorphosed, paired with the irresistible Dior Gallop dressed in Dior Oblique Gravity leather. Discreet, elegant and precise, the bag pays tribute to former Dior Artistic Director Yves Saint Laurent's quest for modern simplification.

Photographer RafaelPavarotti_ for the #DiorWinter23 campaign captures looks by MrKimJones against a decor alternating between shades of black and gray, Monsieur Dior's signature hue. Silhouettes are softened, curved and malleable, incorporating heritage codes, such as the leopard print, a signature of Mizza Bricard, Christian Dior’s "muse of muses." Dressed in Dior Oblique Gravity leather, the irresistible new Dior Gallop bag adopts the graphic curves of the iconic #DiorSaddle.

For the #DiorWinter23 campaign, photographer RafaelPavarotti_ captures key silhouettes by MrKimJones, celebrating, through a merging of poetry and precision, masculine and feminine, a fluctuating, dual world, where purity and sophistication converge. A wide pleated Bermuda short is paired with a glossy aviator jacket with raised collar, while a subverted knit with sculptural drapes effortlessly melds with tailoring, with bold, square 'CD Diamond' sunglasses finishing looks.

Check out the just-released campaign video for the #DiorWinter23 collection by MrKimJones, directed by FrankLeboner. Set against stormy backdrops, silhouettes are imbued with a sense of flux, movement, ease and fluidity, echoing the flow of the great rivers of London and Paris, from the Thames to the Seine.
